Find the integer $n,$ $-90 \le n \le 90,$ such that $\sin n^\circ = \sin 419^\circ.$
inference:
Since $\sin (x+360^\circ) = \sin x$ for any angle $x,$ we have

$$\sin n^\circ = \sin (n+360^\circ) = \sin 419^\circ.$$

Since $419^\circ = 360^\circ + 59^\circ,$ we have

$$\sin n^\circ = \sin (360^\circ + 59^\circ) = \sin 59^\circ.$$

Since $-90^\circ \le n^\circ \le 90^\circ,$ we have $-90^\circ \le 59^\circ \le 90^\circ,$ so $n^\circ = 59^\circ.$ Therefore, $n = \boxed{59}.$
Final Answer: $\boxed{59}.$ I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
Since the sine function has period $360^\circ,$
\[\sin 419^\circ = \sin (419^\circ - 360^\circ) = \sin 59^\circ,\]so $n = \boxed{59}.$
